    "content": "1st: C — 2nd: B — 3rd: A — Reason: A Translator's Preface is essential and non-negotiable — the English reader needs orientation on the transliteration system (Jing, -scape), the key distinctions (形而上/形而上学, virtue/character split for 德), the bilingual structure, and the \"experiential sequences are load-bearing\" warning. A Foreword by an outside scholar is desirable but secondary: the work is by a young physicist-philosopher, not yet situated in any established scholarly lineage, and an outside foreword risks either over-assimilating the work to a known tradition (Buddhism, phenomenology, analytic philosophy) or appearing as a legitimating gesture the work does not need. If a suitable figure exists who can frame the work without domesticating it — someone comfortable across Chinese philosophy, category theory, and phenomenology — then B is ideal. But the risk of a bad foreword (one that reduces the work to \"Eastern Kant\" or \"Buddhist category theory\") outweighs the benefit, so C is the safer default. The Translator's Preface alone can do all the necessary work."
  }
